1.4 The Unfinished Revolution

For all the progress from 2020 to 2026, the revolution is incomplete.

What works:

· Customer service automation (70–80% of routine tickets)
· Code generation and debugging
· Internal knowledge work (research, summarization, analysis)
· Sales lead qualification
· Workflow automation in structured domains

What's still hard:

· Cross-functional workflows involving multiple departments
· Tasks requiring common sense or world knowledge
· High-stakes decisions with significant consequences
· Creative work requiring genuine novelty
· Physical world interaction (though improving rapidly)

What's failing:

· Fully autonomous C-suite agents (abandoned by 2025)
· Unconstrained consumer agents (too many liability issues)
· Agents in highly regulated domains without human oversight
· Multi-agent systems without clear accountability structures

The pattern is clear: agents excel at structured, repeatable tasks with clear success criteria. They struggle with ambiguity, novelty, and high-stakes judgment calls.

The next phase of the revolution will be about extending their reach while managing their limitations.

---

1.5 Why This Acceleration Happened

The speed of change from 2020 to 2026 was unprecedented in enterprise technology. Three factors explain it.

Factor 1: The Model Scaling Hypothesis Proved True

The AI research community had speculated that larger models would yield qualitatively new capabilities. This proved correct. GPT-3 could do things GPT-2 couldn't. GPT-4 could do things GPT-3 couldn't. Each generation unlocked new behaviors—reasoning, tool use, self-correction—that earlier models lacked.

Factor 2: The API Ecosystem Created Flywheels

OpenAI's decision to offer API access created a virtuous cycle. More users meant more feedback. More feedback meant better models. Better models attracted more users. By 2024, millions of developers were building on foundation models, generating improvements that no single lab could have produced alone.

Factor 3: Enterprises Were Ready

Previous AI waves (expert systems, machine learning, deep learning) had taught enterprises how to adopt new technology. The infrastructure was in place. The talent was available. The governance mechanisms, while imperfect, existed. When agents arrived, companies knew how to pilot, evaluate, and scale.

