Chapter 2

Global Landscape: Leaders, Followers, and the New Contenders

---

Introduction: The Geography of Autonomy

The acceleration documented in Chapter 1 did not unfold uniformly across the globe. It never does. Technological revolutions are refracted through local conditions—regulatory regimes, capital availability, cultural attitudes toward automation, and strategic ambitions.

By March 2026, three distinct patterns have emerged.

The United States leads in platform infrastructure and enterprise orchestration. American firms build the foundational models, the orchestration frameworks, and the integration layers that agents run on. If agents are digital workers, the United States builds the operating system.

Europe, and particularly France, charts a different course. Adoption is slower, more structured, and heavily mediated by regulation. The EU AI Act, fully enforceable by 2026, has created a compliance-first environment. European firms do not lead in agent infrastructure—but they may lead in trusted agent deployment.

China pursues scale and strategic autonomy. Chinese agents are deeply integrated into super-app ecosystems, deployed at consumer scale, and increasingly capable of operating autonomously. The Chinese approach tolerates higher autonomy and faster deployment, with less public hand-wringing about governance.

And then there are the new contenders: the Middle East, India, and the Global South. These regions are not waiting for permission. They are building sovereign AI capabilities, national data platforms, and use cases that bypass legacy infrastructure entirely. They may define the next wave of agent adoption.

This chapter surveys each of these regions in turn. The goal is not exhaustive coverage, but a structured understanding of how local conditions shape agent deployment—and what each region can learn from the others.

---

2.1 United States: Platform Leadership and Enterprise Scale

The United States dominates agentic AI for a simple reason: it builds the infrastructure that agents run on.

2.1.1 The Platform Layer

By 2026, the major American AI labs have matured beyond model providers into full-stack agent platforms.

OpenAI offers GPT-4o and the o-series models, with native tool-calling, memory architectures, and multi-step planning capabilities. Enterprise adoption surged after GPT-4-level models demonstrated reliable reasoning on complex, multi-step tasks. OpenAI's API ecosystem now supports thousands of agentic applications, from legal document analysis to financial modeling.

Microsoft has embedded agents into every layer of its enterprise stack. Microsoft 365 Copilot, now in its third generation, includes agents for meeting summarization, workflow automation, code assistance, and sales forecasting. The deep integration with existing enterprise software—Teams, Outlook, Dynamics, GitHub—gives Microsoft a distribution advantage that no competitor can match. By early 2026, agents are not an add-on to Microsoft products; they are the interface.

Anthropic has carved out a distinct position with safety-focused agents, emphasizing constitutional AI principles and transparent reasoning. Claude 3.7, released in late 2025, includes "computer use" capabilities that allow agents to interact with any software application through visual understanding and mouse/keyboard control—a significant step toward general-purpose digital workers.

Google integrates agents across its ecosystem, with Gemini 2 powering everything from search to workspace automation. Google's advantage lies in its data assets and consumer reach; agents can draw on Google's knowledge graph, email, calendar, and maps to execute complex personal and professional tasks.

2.1.2 Enterprise Adoption Metrics

The 2026 Anthropic/Material survey of over 500 U.S. technology leaders provides the clearest picture of enterprise adoption .

Key findings:

· 90% of organizations now use AI in at least one business function, up from 78% a year ago 
· 86% use AI-assisted programming in production, not just experimentation
· 57% have deployed agents in multi-stage workflows
· 42% trust agents to lead development work under human supervision
· 80% report measurable economic returns—not projected, but realized

The survey also reveals how agents are being deployed :

Use Case Organizations Reporting High Impact
Data analysis and reporting 60%
Code generation 59%
Code review and testing 59%
Research and documentation 59%
Planning and ideation 58%
Internal process automation 48%

The even distribution across categories is striking. Agents are not specialized tools for narrow tasks. They are general-purpose capability layers, applied wherever structured knowledge work occurs.

2.1.3 The Infrastructure Race

As agents move from pilots to production, the competitive dynamic is shifting. "This is not about adding AI features," says Jeff Koets, CEO of Nylas. "It is an infrastructure race" .

The Nylas 2026 survey of over 1,000 developers and product leaders found that 94% would consider switching vendors for stronger, more scalable, and compliant agentic capabilities. Sixty-seven percent are already building or shipping agentic workflows, and 85% believe AI agents will become table stakes within three years .

The infrastructure requirements are substantial:

· Clean data layers that agents can reliably access and interpret
· Reliable APIs that support autonomous tool use
· Observability tools to trace agent reasoning and audit actions
· Governance controls embedded in the architecture, not bolted on

Vendors that provide these capabilities will capture the next phase of market growth. Those that don't will be replaced.

2.1.4 The ClickUp Case

Perhaps the most striking U.S. deployment comes from ClickUp, the productivity platform. Founder and CEO Zeb Evans reports: "We now have over 3,258 agents working alongside 1,300 humans. Managers' agents will manage their ICs' agents—overseeing them for human-in-the-loop interactions" .

This is not a pilot. It is a new organizational form: an agent-to-agent management hierarchy, with humans supervising at the top. The implications for workforce design, management practice, and organizational structure are only beginning to be understood.

---

2.2 France: Structured Adoption in a Regulated Environment

France presents a different model. Adoption is slower, more deliberate, and heavily mediated by concerns about trust, transparency, and compliance.

2.2.1 The Cautious Consumer

The Adobe 2026 Digital Trends report, surveying 7,000 consumers and executives across Europe, reveals a distinctly French caution .

Only 30% of French consumers say they would interact with a brand's AI agent if offered—compared to 40% across Europe. Forty-two percent have not considered the idea of a personal AI agent, and 41% are actively closed to it. In Europe as a whole, only 27% express similar resistance.

This is not Luddism. It is a trust deficit—and one with clear conditions for remediation.

The non-negotiables for French consumers :

· Ability to switch to a human: 39% consider this essential (35% Europe)
· Transparency: 31% would stop interacting if they discovered they were speaking to an AI while believing it was human (34% Europe)
· Natural interaction: 68% want AI interactions to feel natural and human, rather than robotic (71% Europe)

The message to enterprises is unambiguous: French consumers will accept agents, but only on terms that preserve human agency, transparency, and conversational quality.

2.2.2 Enterprise Adoption Patterns

French enterprises are moving, but carefully.

Key metrics :

· 74% of French companies report that generative AI has accelerated content ideation and production
· 67% say AI has enabled non-creative teams to produce content
· 78% cite data integration and quality as the main barriers to scaling AI (76% Europe)
· Only 13% have deployed agentic AI at scale for customer support (12% Europe)
· Only 11% for brand discovery and search (11% Europe)
· 36% rate their data quality and accessibility as sufficient for AI (43% Europe)
· 36% have a shared customer data platform for agentic AI (40% Europe)

The pattern is consistent: French enterprises are adopting generative AI for internal productivity gains (content production, ideation), but scaling agentic AI—which requires integration with customer-facing systems and real-time decision-making—proceeds more slowly.

Data readiness is the binding constraint. You cannot build reliable agents on poor data foundations, and French enterprises are honest about their current limitations.

2.2.3 Leadership Perspectives

Sébastien Zins, Vice President for Southern Europe at GitLab, identifies three transformations defining AI maturity in France :

1. The rise of agent platforms

"Many leaders have deployed AI agents in multiple environments—cloud, development, automation—without centralized control. This siloed proliferation generates inefficiency, redundancy, and lack of visibility into their real value."

The response is the emergence of agent platforms as a new infrastructure layer, charged with identifying and organizing existing agents and tracking their performance over time.

2. Human-AI balance

"The goal is no longer to adapt teams to machines, but to design AI that integrates into human workflows and amplifies their performance." In France, 92% of leaders believe companies must prioritize employee training in agentic AI to address skills gaps .

Development teams are becoming orchestrators who guide and supervise AI agents. The companies that succeed will combine human intelligence with agent capabilities.

3. The accountability imperative

As agents consume more resources and influence critical decisions, leadership demands granular transparency into AI performance and ROI. Asset management mechanisms are emerging to track infrastructure costs and actual usage of each agent.

"Accountability becomes the foundation of more advanced maturity that takes risk management and user trust as seriously as economic benefits" .

2.2.4 The French Synthesis

France's approach to agentic AI can be summarized as: compliance-first, trust-based, human-centered.

This is not a failure to adopt. It is a deliberate choice—one that may prove prescient. As agent failures accumulate elsewhere (see Chapter 7), the French emphasis on transparency, accountability, and human oversight may become a competitive advantage rather than a constraint.

