2.3 China: Sovereign Ambition at Scale

China's agentic AI strategy is shaped by three imperatives: strategic autonomy, ecosystem integration, and deployment at massive scale.

2.3.1 Policy Acceleration

The Chinese government has made AI agent development a national priority. The "AI+Manufacturing"专项行动, announced in late 2025 and implemented through 2026, aims for :

· 1000 high-level industrial agents by 2027
· 100 high-quality industrial datasets
· 500 typical application scenarios for promotion
· Safe and reliable supply of core AI technologies

The Ministry of Industry and Information Technology, together with seven other departments, has articulated a clear vision: by 2027, China's AI core technologies will achieve "safe and reliable supply," with industrial scale and empowerment levels ranking among the world's highest .

This is industrial policy applied to software. The state is not merely enabling adoption; it is directing it, setting targets, and mobilizing resources.

2.3.2 Enterprise Players

Three categories of Chinese firms are driving agent deployment.

1. Technology giants

Baidu has integrated agents into search and enterprise tools, developing autonomous digital assistants with deep ecosystem integration. Baidu's ERNIE models power agents across consumer and enterprise applications.

Alibaba offers cloud-based AI agent services, with a focus on e-commerce and logistics automation. Alibaba Cloud provides the infrastructure for thousands of enterprises to build and deploy agents.

Tencent embeds agents into its super-app ecosystem (WeChat), enabling consumer-facing agents for customer service, entertainment, and daily tasks.

2. Specialized agent platforms

The most internationally visible Chinese agent startup has been Manus AI, which built highly autonomous agents capable of executing multi-step digital tasks. In December 2025, Manus was acquired by Meta for approximately $2-3 billion. The deal, involving a Singapore-based but Chinese-founded startup, remains under Chinese export-control review as of early 2026—a reminder that agentic AI is now a matter of national security, not just commerce .

3. Industrial firms

In manufacturing, Chinese companies are deploying agents at unprecedented scale. Huawei's "Manufacturing Agent" concept integrates AI into factory operations. One automaker using Huawei's industrial internet platform reduced order delivery cycles from 14 days to 7 days and improved inventory turnover by 25%. A steel enterprise using AI-powered scheduling saves over 50 million yuan annually in energy costs .

2.3.3 The Inference Challenge

As agents scale, China faces a fundamental economic challenge: inference costs.

Zhou Hongyi, founder of 360 Group and a national political advisor, explains: "When an agent is no longer a 'mouth' that chats, but a 'hand' that works, executing a single task requires repeatedly decomposing steps and trial-and-error searching, consuming hundreds or even thousands of times the tokens of a chat scenario" .

This shifts the economics of AI. Training costs are a one-time investment. Inference costs are recurring—and potentially massive.

The response is a race to build efficient inference infrastructure. In 2025, global tech giants invested heavily: NVIDIA acquired a specialized inference chip company for $200 billion; Amazon, Microsoft, Google, and Meta placed large orders for inference chips from Broadcom. In China, Alibaba announced over 380 billion yuan ($52 billion) in cloud and AI hardware infrastructure over three years. Baidu successfully deployed a self-developed 10,000-card cluster, with plans to expand to 30,000 cards .

The technical requirements for inference differ fundamentally from training. Training needs tightly interconnected clusters where a single card failure can halt the entire process. Inference can scale more flexibly—"as long as memory can hold the model, you can stack machines infinitely, with lower requirements for individual cards and controllable costs" .

This creates an opportunity for China's domestic chip industry. If inference becomes the dominant compute load, and inference can run on less specialized hardware, Chinese chipmakers may have a path to competitiveness without matching NVIDIA's training dominance.

2.3.4 Governance with Chinese Characteristics

Chinese policymakers are attentive to agent risks, but frame them differently than in the West.

Qi Xiangdong, chairman of cybersecurity firm Qi-Anxin Group and a national political advisor, argues: "To achieve dynamic balance between innovation and security, the key is to embed security capabilities throughout the AI lifecycle; clarify compliance red lines; strengthen security主体责任 [primary responsibility] through enhanced permission and content controls; and use AI to fight AI, ensuring security capabilities always stay ahead of risks" .

Xiao Xinguang, chairman of Antiy Labs, calls for a national technology engine for AI security: "Leverage institutional advantages to create a state-led, strategically developed, widely applied 'AI+' national security technology engine" .

The Chinese approach to agent governance is: security by design, state-led coordination, and AI-against-AI defense. It assumes that agents will be attacked, that they will make mistakes, and that the response must be technical and institutional, not just regulatory.

---

2.4 Emerging Markets: The Leapfrog Thesis

The most dynamic agent adoption may be happening outside the traditional technology centers. In the Middle East, India, and parts of Africa, countries are building agentic capabilities without the baggage of legacy infrastructure.

2.4.1 The Middle East: Sovereign AI as National Strategy

The Gulf states are pursuing agentic AI with the same intensity they once applied to oil. The logic is simple: when your national wealth depends on a depleting resource, you invest in the next one.

Key initiatives :

· Sovereign compute and models: Middle Eastern nations are investing in domestically controlled AI infrastructure, enabling local model training and deployment under national policy frameworks. This reduces latency, avoids cross-border data friction, and ensures strategic autonomy.
· National data platforms: Governments are building centralized data assets that can power AI applications across sectors—healthcare, education, transportation, energy.
· Sector-specific adoption programmes: Rather than generic AI strategies, Gulf states are targeting specific industries where AI can deliver measurable impact: grid optimization in energy, fraud detection in banking, citizen services in government.

Farida Gibbs, CEO of Gibbs Consulting, observes: "In the Middle East, we are seeing organisations industrialising AI as part of platform modernisation, product-aligned delivery teams, and a shift from innovation labs to operational ownership" .

The leading sectors reflect this focus: IT infrastructure, banking, government, and energy. These areas benefit from large structured datasets, clear efficiency levers, and direct regulatory or ministerial sponsorship .

2.4.2 India: Talent, Scale, and the SME Opportunity

India's agentic AI trajectory is distinct. It combines a vast pool of technical talent, a massive small-and-medium enterprise sector, and government digital infrastructure that provides a foundation for AI services.

The talent advantage: India produces more AI engineers than any country outside China and the United States. Global capability centers in Indian cities now build agentic systems for multinational parents.

The SME opportunity: India's 60+ million small businesses have largely missed previous enterprise software waves—ERP, CRM, SaaS were too expensive and complex. Agents delivered through mobile interfaces, in local languages, may finally bring automation to this sector. Indic LLMs from startups like Sarvam AI and Krutrim enable agents that understand Hindi, Tamil, Bengali, and other languages, opening markets that text-based interfaces could not reach.

The infrastructure layer: India's Digital Public Infrastructure—UPI for payments, Aadhaar for identity, DigiLocker for documents—provides a ready-made platform for agents that can transact, verify, and access records on behalf of users.

2.4.3 The Leapfrog Thesis

The argument for leapfrog adoption is simple: agents are the first enterprise technology that developing nations can adopt without first building the legacy systems that developed nations must now replace.

A European bank must integrate agents with core banking systems from the 1980s. An Indian fintech can build agent-first, with no legacy constraints. A French retailer must connect agents to decades of accumulated data infrastructure. A Middle Eastern sovereign wealth fund can design data platforms for the agent era from the start.

This does not guarantee success. Data quality, skills gaps, and governance challenges apply everywhere. But it does mean that the next wave of agent innovation may come from unexpected places.

